<h2 id="deliverability">Deliverability: Both Excellent, AWeber Has the Edge</h2>

This is the metric that actually matters for email marketing. Both ConvertKit and AWeber consistently outperform Mailchimp, Sendinblue/Brevo, and most other mid-market platforms on inbox placement.

<p><strong>AWeber's advantage</strong> comes from 25+ years of infrastructure investment. Their dedicated IP pools are managed by a team that monitors sending reputation full-time. ISP relationships developed over decades give AWeber emails a slight edge in placement, particularly with Gmail and Outlook.</p>

<p><strong>ConvertKit's deliverability</strong> is excellent and has improved significantly over the past few years. They've invested heavily in sending infrastructure and actively manage list health. In most real-world scenarios, the deliverability difference between the two is marginal -- maybe 1-3 percentage points on open rates.</p>

<p><strong>My experience:</strong> Open rates on AWeber are consistently 2-3 points higher than ConvertKit for similar content sent to similar audiences. The difference is real but small. Both platforms are in the "your emails actually reach inboxes" tier.</p>

<h2 id="automation">Automation: ConvertKit Is More Modern</h2>

<p><strong>ConvertKit's visual automation builder</strong> is genuinely better. The drag-and-drop interface is clean, conditional branching is intuitive, and the tag-based subscriber model makes complex segmentation natural. You can build multi-path automations that route subscribers based on behavior, tags, and custom fields without fighting the interface.</p>

<p><strong>AWeber's automation builder</strong> works. You can create sequences, add if/else branches, apply tags, and trigger actions based on subscriber behavior. But the interface feels like it was designed five years ago. Building complex automations requires more clicks and the visual feedback is less clear.</p>

<p><strong>For operators specifically:</strong> Most operator email automations are straightforward -- welcome sequences, drip campaigns, RSS-to-email, re-engagement series. Both platforms handle these comfortably. ConvertKit's advantage in automation UX matters more for operators building complex multi-branch sequences. If your automations are linear (and most operator automations are), the difference is minimal.</p>

